How to do this in the Python Mock library: http://www.voidspace.org.uk/python/mock/examples.html#mocking-unbound-methods

This is a super useful feature when your code under test is confusing & difficult to get an exact reference to the instance object itself, or when you will be calling this same method on multiple instance objects.

An example using Mock:
```python
from mock import patch

class Dog(object):
    def bark(self):
        return 'bark'

class TestDog(object):
    @patch.object(Dog, 'bark')
    def test_dog(self, mock_bark):
        mock_bark.return_value = 'foo'

        poodle = Dog()
        result = poodle.bark()

        assert result == 'foo'
```

